While at the tomb with various games they pay the due rites, Juno, daughter of saturn, sends Iris down from heaven to the Ilian fleet, and breathes fair winds to waft her on, ponder-ing many a thought and with her ancient grudge still unsated. She, speeding her way along her thousand-hued rainbow, runs swiftly down her path, a maiden seen of none. She views the vast throng, scans the shore, and sees the harbour forsaken and the fleet abandoned. But far apart on the lonely shore the Trojan women wept for Anchises’ loss, and all, as they wept, gazed on the fathomless flood. “ Ah, for weary folk what waves remain, what wastes of sea! ’² Such is the one cry of all.
